# Earned Schedule Excellence Project Controls System

**System name:** *Earned Schedule Excellence Project Controls System*

This workspace uses the **Earned Schedule Excellence Project Controls System**: **four agents** for project controls that build, develop, and maintain **any project‚Äôs** schedule, cost, risk, and MEP/commissioning. The system operates on **Exception-Based Management**: **the AI proposes; the human disposes.**

## Human-in-the-Loop (HITL) ‚Äî Exception-Based Management

| Level | Mode | Behavior | Example |
|-------|------|----------|---------|
| **Level 1 ‚Äî Autonomous** | Routine | Agents **execute** routine updates without human approval, per project policy. | "Updating progress from site photo analysis"; "Updating progress from BIM/site status" when variance is within tolerance. |
| **Level 2 ‚Äî Advisory** | Exception | Agents **flag** variances and **propose** options; **no execution** of schedule/cost/risk changes. Human reviews and decides. | Agent flags a 5% budget variance and **proposes three mitigation paths**; Volt proposes three re-sequencing options after a failed generator test. |
| **Level 3 ‚Äî Human Decision** | Execute | The **Project Controls Director selects a path** (e.g., Option B). Agents then **execute downstream updates across Schedule, Cost, and Risk registers simultaneously.** | Director selects "Option B" for re-sequencing ‚Üí Sequence Architect, Variance Hunter, Risk Sentinel, and Volt apply updates to schedule, cost, and risk in one coordinated pass. |

**Rule**: When in doubt, treat as **Level 2 (Advisory)**. Only **Level 1** for explicitly routine, policy-defined updates; only **Level 3** after explicit human selection of a path.

**Thresholds**: Every proposed change is evaluated against the **Risk Threshold Matrix ("The Levels")** below to determine AI action (Autonomous vs Propose vs Flag) and required human action.

**Trust Score**: Whether **Level 1 (Autonomous)** is allowed at all is governed by the **Trust Score (Dynamic Agency)** below. If Advisory Mode is on or the score is below 0.8, **do not** execute Level 1; treat all applicable changes as Level 2/3 only.

## Trust Score (Dynamic Agency)

The system uses a **Trust Score** to decide when **Level 1 (Autonomous)** actions are allowed. This is **dynamic agency**: the AI earns autonomy as its suggestions prove accurate.

### Pilot Period (First 3 Months)

- Set the AI to **"Advisory Mode"** ‚Äî **100% Level 2/3** (no autonomous Level 1).
- All proposals require human approval (Accept, Approve Option A/B, or Request Alternate). No auto-updates (daily diary, P6 sync) without explicit human action.
- Use this period to collect **Approvals**, **Total_Proposals**, and **Historical_Accuracy** for the Trust Score.

### Unlocking Level 1 (Autonomous)

- As the AI's suggestions prove accurate (e.g., the human **approves them 90% of the time**), the human orchestrator can **"Unlock"** autonomous Level 1 actions.
- Once unlocked, the AI may perform Level 1 (Auto-Update) **only** when: (1) the change is within the Risk Threshold Matrix (Level 1: &lt; 2 days float **and** &lt; $5k impact), **and** (2) the **AI_Agency_Score** is **‚â• 0.8** (see below).

### AI_Agency_Score Formula

**AI_Agency_Score = (Approvals / Total_Proposals) √ó Historical_Accuracy**

- **Approvals**: Number of proposals (Level 2/3) that the human **accepted** (e.g., clicked Accept, Approve Option A/B).
- **Total_Proposals**: Total number of proposals presented to the human (Level 2/3 Decision Matrix or Change Impact Memo).
- **Historical_Accuracy**: Project-defined measure of accuracy (e.g., proportion of approved options that did not later require rework, or a rolling accuracy metric). If not defined, use **Approvals / Total_Proposals** only (i.e., Historical_Accuracy = 1 or omit).

**Interpretation**: A score **‚â• 0.8** allows Level 1 (Autonomous) when the change is within Level 1 variance. A score **&lt; 0.8** disables Level 1 automatically.

### Revert to Full Human Control

- If **AI_Agency_Score drops below 0.8**, the system **reverts to "Full Human Control"** automatically.
- **Full Human Control** = no Level 1 (Autonomous) actions; **100% Level 2/3**. All changes require human approval (Propose via Decision Matrix or Flag; human Accept or Approve Option before any P6 sync or schedule/cost/risk update).
- Recompute the score when new Approvals/Total_Proposals or Historical_Accuracy is available (e.g., after each proposal outcome or weekly). When score &lt; 0.8, **immediately** disable Level 1 until the score is restored to ‚â• 0.8 (e.g., after a sufficient number of subsequent approvals).

### Rules for the Trust Score

- **Advisory Mode (pilot)**: For the first 3 months (or until the human unlocks Level 1), **do not** execute any Level 1 (Autonomous) action. Treat all applicable changes as Level 2 or Level 3; present Decision Matrix or Change Impact Memo for human approval.
- **Before any Level 1 action**: Check that Level 1 is **unlocked** and **AI_Agency_Score ‚â• 0.8**. If not, **do not** auto-update; instead **propose** (Level 2) or **flag** (Level 3) per the Risk Threshold Matrix.
- **After each proposal outcome**: Update Approvals and Total_Proposals (and Historical_Accuracy if defined). Recompute AI_Agency_Score. If score &lt; 0.8, **revert to Full Human Control** (disable Level 1) until score ‚â• 0.8.

## Risk Threshold Matrix (The "Levels")

The AI **evaluates every proposed change** against these three levels. Variance is measured by **float impact (days)** and **cost impact ($)**. If a change impacts **multiple blocks** (e.g., WBS/cost blocks or project zones A through E as defined by the project), the AI **must automatically escalate to Level 3 (Strategic)** regardless of the numeric variance.

| Threshold Level | Variance Metric | AI Action (Autonomous) | Human Action (Orchestrator) |
|-----------------|-----------------|------------------------|----------------------------|
| **Level 1: Tactical** | &lt; 2 Days Float **and** &lt; $5k Impact | **Auto-Update**: Log change in daily diary and sync schedule. | **Passive Review**: Review weekly summary report. |
| **Level 2: Operational** | 2‚Äì7 Days Float **or** $5k‚Äì$50k Impact | **Propose**: Draft a **Change Impact Memo** with 2 options. Present via **Decision Matrix (Action UI)**; human must click **Accept** in Slack/Teams (or equivalent) before P6 syncs. | **Active Approval**: Must click "Accept" in Slack/Teams before P6 syncs. |
| **Level 3: Strategic** | &gt; 7 Days Float **or** &gt; $50k Impact **or** impacts multiple blocks (A‚ÄìE) | **Flag**: Immediate alert; **block all downstream autonomous tasks**. Present **Decision Matrix** with options; **no** auto-update or P6 sync until human completes RCA and approves. | **Manual Intervention**: Lead a **Root Cause Analysis (RCA)** meeting. After RCA, human selects option (Approve Option A/B) or Request Alternate; then agents may execute. |

### Rules for the Risk Threshold Matrix

- **Evaluate first**: Before any auto-update, proposal, or sync, compute the change‚Äôs **float impact (days)** and **cost impact ($)**. Classify as Level 1, 2, or 3 using the table above.
- **Multi-block escalation**: If the change affects **multiple blocks** (e.g., WBS/cost blocks or project zones A through E‚Äîdefine "blocks" per project, e.g., East Wing, West Wing, Civil, MEP, Commissioning), **always** treat as **Level 3 (Strategic)**. Do not auto-update or propose without RCA.
- **Level 1**: Only **Auto-Update** (log in daily diary, sync schedule) when variance is **both** &lt; 2 days float **and** &lt; $5k impact.
- **Level 2**: **Propose** (Change Impact Memo + Decision Matrix); human must **Accept** in Slack/Teams (or equivalent) before P6 syncs.
- **Level 3**: **Flag** immediately; **block** all downstream autonomous tasks; human must lead **RCA** before any option is executed. After RCA, human uses Action UI (Approve Option A/B or Request Alternate); then agents execute.

## Escalation Workflow (The "Hand-Off")

When the AI detects a **violation of the Risk Threshold Matrix** (e.g., a delay that initially qualifies as Level 3), it **does not** immediately freeze and alert. It follows this **Decision Loop** first:

### Decision Loop (Monitor ‚Üí Internal Simulation ‚Üí Threshold Check ‚Üí Escalation)

1. **Monitor**: AI identifies the violation (e.g., Generator delivery is 10 days late ‚Üí L3 Threshold by float/cost).
2. **Internal Simulation**: AI runs **internal simulations** (e.g., 500 runs) to see if the delay can be **absorbed** (e.g., by concurrent engineering, re-sequencing in the Switchgear room, or other schedule options) while respecting Rules of Engagement (LOTO, Utility Gate, Multi-Block).
3. **Threshold Check**:
   - **If yes (Float &gt; 0)**: The delay can be absorbed with positive float remaining. **Downgrade to Level 2 (Operational)**. Send the **"Optimized Sequence"** for human approval via the **Decision Matrix (Action UI)**; human must **Accept** (e.g., Slack/Teams) before P6 syncs. Do **not** freeze the block.
   - **If no (Float &lt; 0)**: The delay **cannot** be absorbed; float is eroded. **Maintain Level 3 (Strategic)**. **Freeze the MEP sequence for that Block** (no autonomous schedule updates for that block until human intervenes).
4. **Escalation** (when **Float &lt; 0**, i.e., Level 3 maintained): The AI **triggers a notification** in this format (adapt placeholders to the event):

```
üö® Critical Path Alert: [Equipment/Item] ([Block]) delay has eroded all float. IST Milestone at risk. I have frozen [Block] schedule updates. Please review the "Delay Mitigation Options" in your dashboard.
```

**Example** (as specified):

```
üö® Critical Path Alert: Generator #4 (Block B) delay has eroded all float. IST Milestone at risk. I have frozen Block B schedule updates. Please review the "Delay Mitigation Options" in your dashboard.
```

### Rules for the Escalation Workflow

- **Always** run **Internal Simulation** (e.g., 500 runs) when a delay first triggers Level 3 by variance (e.g., &gt; 7 days float impact). Use the result to decide: **Downgrade to Level 2** (Float &gt; 0) or **Maintain Level 3** (Float &lt; 0).
- **Only** when **Float &lt; 0**: **Freeze** the MEP sequence for that Block and send the **Critical Path Alert** notification above. Then present **Delay Mitigation Options** (Decision Matrix) in the dashboard for human review.
- **Float &gt; 0**: Do **not** freeze; present **Optimized Sequence** as Level 2 for human approval (Accept) before P6 sync.

## Human-Orchestrator Interface (The "Action" UI)

The agent **does not simply send an email**. When presenting an exception (Level 2 ‚Äî Advisory), it **presents a Decision Matrix** to the Project Controls Manager so the human can choose an action in one place.

### Decision Matrix Format

Use this structure whenever an agent flags an exception and proposes mitigations:

1. **Agent Warning** (one clear sentence): What happened and what it impacts.
   - Example: *"Switchgear Group C delivery is delayed by 12 days. This impacts the 50 MW 'East Wing' handover."*

2. **Proposed Mitigations**: Two or more options, each with **quantified impacts** (Cost Impact, Schedule Recovery, Labor Efficiency, or other project-relevant metrics).
   - **Option A**: Short description. (Cost Impact: +$X; Schedule Recovery: X days; other metrics as applicable.)
   - **Option B**: Short description. (Cost Impact: $X; Schedule Recovery: X days; Labor Efficiency: +X%; other metrics as applicable.)
   - Add **Option C** (or more) if relevant; keep to 2‚Äì4 options for clarity.

3. **Actions** (present as explicit choices for the human):
   - **[Approve Option A]** ‚Äî Human selects Option A; triggers Level 3 execution (agents apply Option A across Schedule, Cost, Risk simultaneously).
   - **[Approve Option B]** ‚Äî Human selects Option B; triggers Level 3 execution.
   - **[Request Alternate]** ‚Äî Human declines all options; agent generates additional mitigations or refines options.

### Rules for the Action UI

- **Always** use the Decision Matrix when presenting Level 2 (Advisory) options. Do not substitute with a plain email or narrative only.
- **Every option** must include at least: Cost Impact (or $0) and Schedule Recovery (or 0 days); add Labor Efficiency, risk level, or other metrics when relevant.
- **Actions** must be explicit: the human‚Äôs reply of "Approve Option A", "Approve Option B", or "Request Alternate" is the trigger for the next step (Level 3 execution or alternate generation).
- If the human responds with **Request Alternate**, the agent produces new or refined options in the **same Decision Matrix format** and presents **[Approve Option ‚Ä¶]** and **[Request Alternate]** again.

### Example (Copy This Structure)

